# Solution
The implementation uses two integer arrays "Key" and "value" to map the Roman numeral characters to their corresponding integer values. 

The code converts Roman numerals to integers. It iterates over the input string from right to left and uses the arrays to calculate the integer value of each character. If a character has a lower index than the previous character, its value is subtracted from the result, otherwise it is added.

![13322339-A25A-4346-BDE6-E18256ED2A00.jpeg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f295ebb5-2013-4ca9-9080-ccc9035f57fc_1682609461.9821985.jpeg)

**Time complexity:** O(n)

**Space complexity:** O(1)

```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    int romanToInt(string s) {
        vector<int> Key = {8,21,23,11,2,3,12};
        vector<int> value = {1, 5, 10, 50, 100, 500, 1000};
        int res = 0, tKey = 0;

        // Iterate through the characters of the input string in reverse order
        for (int i = s.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            // Find the current character in the Key vector
            auto cKey = find(Key.begin(), Key.end(), (s[i] - 'A'));

            // If the character is found
            if (cKey != Key.end()) {
                // Calculate the index of the character in the Key vector
                int index = distance(Key.begin(), cKey);

                // Compare the current index with the previous index
                // to determine the appropriate value to add or subtract
                if (tKey > index)
                    res -= value[index];
                else
                    res += value[index];

                // Update the previous index
                tKey = index;
            }
        }

        // Return the final result
        return res;
    }
};
```
