# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind this solution is to map the string set with their corresponding integer values and return the answer with help of some integer values

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. first we will take a roman array vector which will contain the corresponding integer value of the respective roman string.
2. we will take an ***ans*** variable which is initialised to 0 and return the final integer value of the corresponding roman string.
3. now we will iterate through every character of the string and check for the corresponding value.
        - Now there will be  2 cases
   - **case 1-**  if(roman[s[i]]<roman[s[i+1]])
                        {
                    ans=ans+roman[s[i+1]]-roman[s[i]]-roman[s[i+1]];
                        }
Here, I have written ans=ans+roman[s[i+1]]-roman[s[i]]-roman[s[i+1]]; just for the sake of better understanding that the characters from index=1 to index=n-1 will be repeated, so they need to cancel out 
So the final answer for this case will be: **ans=ans-roman[s[i]]**;

   - **case 2-** if(roman[s[i]]>=roman[s[i+1]])
                        {
                ans+=roman[s[i]]+roman[s[i+1]]-roman[s[i+1]];
            } 
Here also, I have written ans=ans+roman[s[i]]+roman[s[i+1]]-roman[s[i+1]];as index=2 to index=n are repeating twice,so they need to be subtracted,
But here the integer value corresponding to the roman is either greater or equal to the value with the succeeding index
So the final answer for this case will be: **ans=ans+roman[s[i]]**;


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
    **Time: O(n)**
Each character is traversed once only, so linear time complexity.

- Space complexity:
    **Space: O(128) = O(1)**
there will be only constants i.e roman(128) so only constant space complexity.

# Code
