solutions.content:
Handbook case for a nice backtracking application here!

In order to solve ths problem, we will declare a few class variable to share data between our main function and the `dfs` helper one:
* `res` is going to be our usual accumulator variable, where we will store all the paths that qualify;
* `tmp` is the temporary path we will weave and unweave as we go in our DFS exploration of the tree and subsequently backtrack it;
* `target` will store a copy of the original input of the same name, not to have to pass it at each recursive call;
* `tmpVal` will store our current sum of values, initially set to `0`.

In our main function, we will first of all rule out the edge case of an empty tree, assign the value to the class version of `target` and then call `dfs` passing `root` as its sole parameter.

This helper function will:
* assign `root->val` to `val`;
* make use of it, pushing it into `tmp` and summing it to `tmpVal`;
* check ifwe are on a leaf and if the newly updated value of `tmpVal` equals `target`, in which case we know we can add `tmp` to `res`;
* call recursively `dfs` on the `left` and `right` branch, provided they exist;
* backtrack what we did in the second step, resetting `tmp` (with a pop) and `tmpVal` (with a simple subtraction) to their original values.

Once done, we can just `return` `res` and be done :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
    vector<vector<int>> res;
    vector<int> tmp;
    int target, tmpVal = 0;
    void dfs(TreeNode *root) {
        // support variables
        int val = root->val;
        // adding the current value to tmp
        tmp.push_back(val), tmpVal += val;
        // checking if it meets the condition
        if (!root->left && !root->right && tmpVal == target) res.push_back(tmp);
        // recursive calls
        if (root->left) dfs(root->left);
        if (root->right) dfs(root->right);
        // backtracking
        tmp.pop_back(), tmpVal -= val;
    }
public:
    vector<vector<int>> pathSum(TreeNode *root, int target) {
        // edge case: empty tree
        if (!root) return {};
        this->target = target;
        dfs(root);
        return res;
    }
};
```

Curiously, this version of `dfs` which does not store `val` seems to not just consume a bit less memory as expected, but also to run a bit faster on average:

```cpp
    void dfs(TreeNode *root) {
        // adding the current value to tmp
        tmp.push_back(root->val), tmpVal += root->val;
        // checking if it meets the condition
        if (!root->left && !root->right && tmpVal == target) res.push_back(tmp);
        // recursive calls
        if (root->left) dfs(root->left);
        if (root->right) dfs(root->right);
        // backtracking
        tmp.pop_back(), tmpVal -= root->val;
    }
```

And just for the lolZ, created also a BFS version.

I tried to optimise as much as possible, queuing a data structure that stores the last node used and a pair of previous values seen and their total, but it was of course much slower and draining about double the memory of the other approach; still fun to fiddle with it a bit:

```cpp
using path = pair<TreeNode*, pair<vector<int>, int>>;

class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> pathSum(TreeNode *root, int target) {
        // edge case: empty tree
        if (!root) return {};
        // support variables
        vector<vector<int>> res;
        vector<int> tmp;
        queue<path> q;
        int qLen = 1;
        q.push({root, {{root->val}, root->val}});
        // BFS
        while (qLen) {
            while (qLen--) {
                // extracting the front
                path curr = q.front();
                q.pop();
                // checking for matching leafs
                if (!curr.first->left && !curr.first->right && curr.second.second == target)
                    res.push_back(curr.second.first);
